The key insight in this solution is to use the property that for any invertible element $x$ modulo $n$, $x \cdot x^{-1} \equiv 1 \pmod n$. By multiplying the expression $(a+b)^{-1}(a^{-1}+b^{-1})$ by $(ab)(ab)^{-1}$, which is equivalent to 1 modulo $n$, we can simplify the expression and arrive at the desired result.
1. Start with the expression $(a+b)^{-1}(a^{-1}+b^{-1})$.
2. Multiply the expression by $(ab)(ab)^{-1}$, which is equivalent to 1 modulo $n$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   (a+b)^{-1}(a^{-1}+b^{-1})(ab)(ab)^{-1}
   \end{align*}$$
3. Expand the product:
   $$\begin{align*}
   (a+b)^{-1}(a^{-1}ab+abb^{-1})(ab)^{-1}
   \end{align*}$$
4. Simplify using the properties $a^{-1}a \equiv 1 \pmod n$ and $bb^{-1} \equiv 1 \pmod n$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   (a+b)^{-1}(a+b)(ab)^{-1}
   \end{align*}$$
5. Cancel out $(a+b)^{-1}(a+b)$, which is equivalent to 1 modulo $n$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   (ab)^{-1}
   \end{align*}$$
6. Use the given condition $(ab)^{-1} \equiv 2 \pmod n$ to obtain the final result.
